 in which they were created and sited, arguing that even the apparently coarse images to be found beneath choir stalls are intimately linked to the devotional life of the medieval English Church. The analysis is complemented by a gazetteer of the most notable instances. Dr Paul Hardwickis Professor in English, Leeds Trinity University College.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBenchendszEngland. 0aChristian art and symbolismzEnglandyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aChurch architecturexDetails. 0aChurch architecturezEnglandxDetails. 0aChurch furniturezEngland. 0aMisericordszEngland. 0aWood-carving, MedievalzEngland. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aEnglish Medieval.  aEuropean contexts.  aMisericords.  abelief.  achurch stalls.  achurch.  adevotional life.  adevotional milieu.  adoctrinal.  aeveryday.  afantastic.  agazetteer.  alate middle ages.  alife.  amedieval art.  amotifs.  anotable instances.  aprofane.  areligious context.  asacred.  ascatological.  aspiritual.  athemes.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615962640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159626423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159626/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles